original_text: a delayed marksheet from cbse and the stupid policies of the university have completely ruined my career  .   .  my revised marksheet had an increase of more than 20 marks making my percentage so good that i had cleared the cut off of st stephens also for certain subjects  .  however i still couldn't make it to the college of my choice  .  two of the top 5 colleges of the uni which i went to refused to admit me saying that general quota has been over admitted already we are open only for reserved classes now  .  .  from begging to requesting  ,  appealing and even showing them the section in the du prospectus which clearly states that revised mark sheets will be considered ( it doesn't mention anything about over admission or any other condition  ?  ) speaking to hod's  ,  principals and other officials i did every possible thing  .  however all efforts went waste  .   .  today i am stuck in an off campus college which has no infrastructure no teacher's and is practically in the middle of nowhere  .  and most people of du dont even know this college exists  .  .  .  .
translated_text: A delayed marksheet from CBSE and the university's stupid policies have completely ruined my career. My revised marksheet showed an increase of more than 20 marks, making my percentage so good that I had cleared the cut-off for St. Stephen's for certain subjects. However, I still couldn't get into the college of my choice. Two of the top 5 colleges of the university that I approached refused to admit me, saying that the general quota has already been over-admitted and they are only open for reserved categories now. From begging to requesting, appealing, and even showing them the section in the DU prospectus which clearly states that revised marksheets will be considered (it doesn't mention anything about over-admission or any other condition?), speaking to HODs, principals, and other officials, I did everything possible. However, all efforts went to waste. Today, I am stuck in an off-campus college that has no infrastructure, no teachers, and is practically in the middle of nowhere. Most people at DU don't even know this college exists.

translated_text: These old people can be so cunning, right? Just yesterday, I was traveling on the metro, and at Rajeev Chowk, an elderly uncle got on who was very frail and couldn't even stand properly. Seeing him, my emotions stirred, and I offered him my seat. He was very happy and sat down. At the next station, a sweet girl got on and stood next to me. That old man offered her his seat and stood up himself, giving me a sly smile from a distance. Everyone was looking at me as if I had done something wrong. I felt so bad, then thought, "Forget it, this is the age of Kalyug, there's no place for goodness here anymore." But still, I felt really bad, thinking that maybe if I had given the seat to someone else, they wouldn't have done that. Felt a guilt.
